import type { FeelingsContext } from '../card-feelings-extended'

// Wands suit: Ace through King (14 cards)
export const WANDS: Record<string, FeelingsContext> = {
  'ace-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Ace of Wands as feelings is a fresh, unmistakable spark of attraction. When this card describes how someone feels about you, they have caught fire — quickly, often before they have had time to think about whether they should. There is desire here, but also delight: they are excited by you, energised by your presence, drawn to the version of themselves they become in your orbit. The feeling is not subtle. They want to act on it, talk about it, see you sooner rather than later.\n\nThis is a fire-element opening, which means the emotion is hot but not necessarily reflective. They may not yet understand exactly why you affect them this way — only that you do. Expect impulsive messages, sudden suggestions to meet, a willingness to rearrange plans to make space for you. Wands feelings express themselves readily; this person is unlikely to be hiding what they feel, though they may be hiding how much they feel it, because the intensity has surprised them too.\n\nIf you are wondering whether their interest is real, the Ace of Wands says yes — at this moment, absolutely. The honest caveat is that an Ace is a beginning, not a guarantee of duration. Fire that ignites quickly can also burn unevenly if neither of you tends it. For now, though, honour what is here. Their feelings are genuine, fresh and alive, and they are quietly hoping you feel something similar in return.`,
    reversedLong: `The Ace of Wands reversed as feelings describes a spark that wants to ignite but keeps stalling. The other person feels something — there is real attraction or interest in the picture — yet the flame is not catching cleanly. They may be hesitating because of timing, because of an old wound that taught them to distrust quick chemistry, or because some part of their life is too crowded right now to make space for new fire. The feeling is real; the conditions are wrong.\n\nReversed, this card can also describe somebody whose enthusiasm has cooled since the early days. The initial heat was authentic, but it was not tended, and now what remains is a pilot light rather than a flame. They still notice you. They still feel pulled toward you. They are simply no longer acting on it with the urgency they once did, and the silence in between meetings or messages has grown longer.\n\nThe other possibility, less comfortable but worth naming, is that they were performing passion they did not actually feel. Wands fire is honest when it is real; when it is forced, it sputters. If their attention has gone vague or their words have grown disproportionate to their behaviour, the Ace reversed may be quietly telling you that the spark was theirs to ignite and they have already let it go out. Read their actions, not their declarations, and trust the rhythm of their actual presence.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel a quick, electric pull toward you that they are still getting used to. Something about you has switched a light on inside them, and they are noticing the brightness of their own attention every time you cross their mind. The feeling is closer to excitement than calm — a slight flutter, a quicker pulse, a willingness to think about you at inconvenient hours. They want to see you, talk to you, hear you laugh; the wanting itself feels like a small adventure they have not had in a while.\n\nWhat they may not yet say out loud is how surprised they are. People with this card around them often feel slightly off-balance, in the best way. Expect them to express it through action more than analysis: a sudden message, an unexpected invitation, a small gesture that surprises you. Their feelings are warm, fresh and unmistakably interested. The energy is asking to grow, and they are quietly hoping you will meet it.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Ace of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Ace of Wands as feelings is fresh attraction igniting in real time. The other person is experiencing a burst of desire, curiosity and excitement about you — often more intensely than they expected. This is not a slow-burn feeling; it is a spark that has already lit. They want to act on it, see you, learn more about you. Expect spontaneous messages, suggestions to meet, energy you can feel coming through the screen. The honest caveat is that Aces are beginnings, not promises of longevity, but the present feeling is unmistakably real and alive.' },
      { q: 'Does Ace of Wands mean they like me?', a: 'Yes. The Ace of Wands as feelings is one of the clearest signs of genuine attraction in the deck. They like you, they are excited by you, and they are likely already imagining what could happen next. This card describes initial chemistry that the other person has noticed and is responding to rather than suppressing. Whether the spark develops into something durable depends on what you both do with it, but the question of whether they feel something is settled. They do, and they want you to notice.' },
      { q: 'Is Ace of Wands reversed a good sign for feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Ace of Wands describes a spark that has not quite caught — attraction is present but stalled. They may feel pulled toward you yet hesitant to act, blocked by timing, fear or competing demands. It is not a hard no; it is a soft, uncertain maybe. Read their actions more than their words. If real feeling is there, it usually finds a way to express itself, even slowly. If their attention has gone vague, the reversal may be quietly saying the flame they had has already cooled.' },
      { q: 'What does Ace of Wands mean for a new relationship?', a: 'For a new relationship, the Ace of Wands as feelings is an excellent omen of mutual heat. The other person is genuinely fired up by you and likely to move quickly to spend more time together. Honour the intensity without rushing past the basics — this fire is real, but real fires also benefit from sturdy hearths. Let them show you who they are through how they pursue the connection. If the energy holds steady through the first few weeks rather than burning out fast, you have the makings of something with both passion and substance.' },
    ],
  },

  'two-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Two of Wands as feelings describes someone who is taking you seriously enough to plan around you. They have moved past the first flush of curiosity and are now standing on their own balcony, looking out at a horizon that has begun to include you. There is desire here — Wands always carry heat — but the dominant note is consideration. They are thinking about what a future with you could look like, weighing options, imagining timelines. You are no longer a passing thought; you are a possibility they are mapping.\n\nThis is the feeling of someone who likes you and is also slightly cautious about getting it right. They may not be the fastest mover. Their messages can come in considered, measured intervals rather than impulsive bursts, and their enthusiasm shows up in plans more than poetry. Trust the pattern. The Two of Wands person is not playing it cool to be aloof; they are pacing themselves because they want this to matter.\n\nThere is also an element of ambition mixed into the attraction. They tend to feel most drawn to people who fit into the broader life they are building, and your presence has prompted some inner reshuffling. They are asking themselves whether the future they were heading toward should now include you — and increasingly, the answer is yes. The feeling is genuine, focused and patient. They are choosing you on purpose, and that choice is the heat underneath the calm.`,
    reversedLong: `The Two of Wands reversed as feelings describes someone caught in indecision about you. They feel something — the attraction is not in question — but they cannot quite commit to acting on it with the boldness it deserves. There is a smaller horizon in the way: fear of disrupting their current life, attachment to a familiar but limiting routine, or simply a habit of keeping options open instead of choosing one. You are on their map; they are just not certain whether to set sail.\n\nReversed, this card can also flag somebody who is dating you while privately running a quiet shortlist of other possibilities. This is not always cynical. Sometimes it reflects fear of getting it wrong rather than a lack of feeling for you. But the experience on your end is the same: their warmth comes and goes, their plans for the future stay deliberately vague, and you find yourself wondering whether you are the destination or merely a stop along the way.\n\nThe gentler reading is that they need more time, information or courage before they can fully step toward you. The harder reading is that their indecision is itself the answer — that someone genuinely fired up about you would have planted a flag by now. Watch what they do over the next handful of weeks, not what they say in any one tender moment. The Two of Wands reversed person reveals themselves in patterns. Where they spend their actual time tells you where their heart has been pointing all along.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel pulled toward you and also a little quiet about it. They are thinking — perhaps more than you realise — about what a future with you might look like, sketching scenarios in private, noticing how often their mind drifts in your direction when it should be elsewhere. The attraction is real, but they are letting it settle into something they can act on with confidence rather than impulse. Expect their pace to be steadier than passionate, their planning more telling than their poetry.\n\nWhat they may not say outright is that you have shifted their horizon. Where they were going on their own has started to look different with you in the picture, and that is a serious thing for this person to admit. They are weighing how to bring you into a bigger plan, not whether to. Trust the slower rhythm. Their feelings are warm, considered and quietly ambitious — they want this to work, and they are pacing themselves to make sure it does.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Two of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Two of Wands as feelings describes considered, planning-stage attraction. The other person is genuinely drawn to you and has begun thinking about you in the context of a longer-term future. Their pace will feel steadier than the Ace of Wands rush — fewer impulsive messages, more deliberate plans. The heat is real; it is simply being channelled into thought as well as desire. They are deciding on purpose, weighing how you fit into their bigger life, and that careful interest is its own kind of compliment.' },
      { q: 'Is Two of Wands a good sign for love?', a: 'Yes, the Two of Wands is a constructive love omen. It describes someone who is not just attracted to you in passing but is actively considering whether to build something with you. The card honours patience and planning — the kind of energy that leads to durable partnership rather than fleeting chemistry. Their pace may feel slower than you would like, but the depth of their consideration is the substance underneath. They are choosing you with intention, and that intention is precisely what makes the connection worth waiting for.' },
      { q: 'What does Two of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Two of Wands describes feelings tangled with indecision. They are attracted to you but cannot quite commit to acting on it boldly, often because fear, competing options or a too-small horizon are getting in the way. The warmth is real; the willingness to choose is wobbly. Watch their patterns over time rather than holding to any one tender moment. If the indecision keeps repeating, it is becoming the answer. Real interest, after enough time, eventually plants a flag.' },
      { q: 'Does Two of Wands mean they are thinking about me?', a: 'Yes — significantly more than they probably let on. The Two of Wands as feelings is the card of someone quietly drafting a future that includes you. They are running scenarios in their head, noticing where you fit, considering what next steps might look like. Their outer pace can feel measured, but their inner attention is anything but. If you have been wondering whether you cross their mind often, this card is a strong yes. They are thinking, planning and deciding, with you firmly inside the frame.' },
    ],
  },

  'three-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Three of Wands as feelings describes someone whose attraction to you has matured into anticipation. They are no longer just sparked by you or planning around you; they are now watching the horizon, expecting you. Whatever they set in motion — the conversation, the date, the move toward something more serious — they trust will return in good time. There is patience here, but it is the patience of someone confident that what they want is coming, not the patience of someone unsure.\n\nThis card often appears when distance is in the picture. They may live in a different city, travel for work, or simply be in a season of life that keeps you apart more than either of you would like. The Three of Wands says the distance is not weakening their feeling; if anything, it is sharpening it. They miss you in a way that has its own steady warmth, and they are willing to wait — to plan, to coordinate, to invest in the eventual reunion rather than chase a faster fix.\n\nThe deeper feeling here is expansion. They sense that you are part of a bigger life they are building, not a side chapter. Their attraction is paired with a kind of vision: a sense that meeting you was meaningful, that the connection has scope, that there is more ahead than what is visible right now. Trust the longer view. Their feelings are confident, expansive and oriented toward a shared horizon that they already feel is well on its way.`,
    reversedLong: `The Three of Wands reversed as feelings describes someone whose anticipation has hit delays they did not foresee. They had feelings for you; they imagined something developing; and then life intervened — a job, a family situation, a previous relationship that has taken longer to close than they hoped. The ships are not arriving on schedule, and they may be quietly frustrated by their own inability to show up for you in the way they had pictured.\n\nReversed, this card can also describe a missed window. They felt something real, perhaps even significant, but the timing was off by inches and they did not act when the moment was open. Now they may still be thinking of you with regret or longing, but the practical chance has narrowed. Their feelings are sincere; their position is awkward. They may not know how to recover the moment, or whether you would even welcome the attempt.\n\nThe softer version of this reversal is simply impatience. They want more from the connection than current circumstances allow, and the gap between desire and reality has begun to grate. Their feelings are still warm, but their confidence in the future has wobbled. If you sense this is what is happening, a clear, kind conversation about timelines and expectations can do real work here. The Three of Wands reversed responds well to honest reforecasting between two people who still care, and badly to indefinite drift between two people who are pretending they do not.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel a kind of warm, patient longing for you. They have already invested feeling in this connection, and they are looking ahead rather than questioning what is here. Even if circumstances are keeping you physically or emotionally apart, their attention keeps drifting toward you with a quiet certainty that you will meet again, or meet more deeply, or finally land in the same chapter. The waiting itself is something they are willing to hold, because they trust that what is between you is real.\n\nThere is also a sense of expansion in how they think about you. You are not a casual presence in their mind; you are linked to a bigger vision of how their life could feel. Whether or not they have told you this in plain words, they are imagining a future that includes you and pacing themselves toward it. Their feelings are confident, steady and quietly excited. They are not in a rush, but they are not letting go either.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Three of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Three of Wands as feelings describes mature anticipation. The other person is past the initial spark and now in the steady phase of looking forward to more with you. They are confident in their attraction, often patient with distance or timing, and oriented toward a longer horizon. Their feelings are not just present-tense desire; they are forward-tense investment. They believe something is coming between you, and they are watching for it the way you watch for sails on the water — without anxiety, with quiet expectation.' },
      { q: 'Does Three of Wands mean they miss me?', a: 'Yes, particularly if distance is a real factor in your situation. The Three of Wands as feelings often appears when the other person is thinking about you from elsewhere — another city, another phase of life, another commitment that has kept you apart. They are not letting the distance erode their warmth. If anything, the gap has clarified what they want, and they are looking forward to closing it. Their missing you is steady and confident rather than desperate, which is one of the kinder qualities of this card.' },
      { q: 'What does Three of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Three of Wands describes feelings interrupted by delays, missed timing or impatience with circumstances. The attraction is real but the practical alignment has gone wrong. They may still care about you, may still want more, but the situation has not delivered what either of you hoped. This card responds well to an honest, kind conversation about timelines. Pretending the gap is fine when it is not tends to let the feeling quietly dissipate, while naming it often clears space for the connection to recover.' },
      { q: 'Is Three of Wands a sign of long-distance love?', a: 'Often, yes. The Three of Wands carries the imagery of ships on the horizon — distance, expectation and the patience to wait for what is coming. Many querents draw this card when navigating long-distance romance, and it tends to be encouraging: the connection is real, the feelings are durable, and the time apart is not eroding what you have. The card also rewards visible planning. If you both keep building toward a shared horizon, the distance is a chapter, not the whole story.' },
    ],
  },

  'four-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Four of Wands as feelings describes warmth that has begun to feel like home. The other person is not only attracted to you; they are at ease around you in a way that surprises and delights them. Being with you feels celebratory in the best, most ordinary sense — like the room is brighter, the conversation is easier, the future is something they can imagine in cheerful detail rather than abstract longing. There is romantic heat here, but the bigger note is belonging.\n\nThis card often shows up around milestones: meeting friends or family, planning a trip together, moving in, an engagement, or simply the quiet realisation that the relationship has crossed an invisible threshold and become serious. They feel proud to be connected to you. They want to show you off without strain — not to perform, but because their delight is hard to contain. If they have been guarded with previous partners, the Four of Wands says they have lowered the drawbridge with you and are finding it a relief rather than a risk.\n\nThe deeper feeling is one of integration. They are no longer compartmentalising you from the rest of their life; you are being woven in, and they are pleased to find that you fit. Expect invitations into their wider world — community, family, traditions — that are signs of how seriously they are taking what you share. Their feelings are warm, settled and quietly joyful. They want this to last, and they want the people who matter to them to know that you are part of why.`,
    reversedLong: `The Four of Wands reversed as feelings describes warmth that exists but cannot quite settle. They may genuinely care for you, even love you, but something in their current life is making the comfortable, celebratory version of this relationship hard to inhabit. Family pressure, unresolved past commitments, conflicting timelines or simply private uncertainty about readiness are crowding the hearth. They want to feel at home with you; they just cannot yet.\n\nReversed, this card can also describe somebody who is performing the milestone without inhabiting it emotionally. The photo went up. The announcement was made. The moving boxes are in the hallway. But their inner experience has not caught up with the outer commitment, and the gap is producing strain. They may be more anxious than they show — worried they have rushed, worried they have disappointed someone, worried that the public version of this relationship is no longer matching the private feeling.\n\nThe kinder version of this reversal is friction that can be repaired by honesty. If you sense their warmth is intact but their comfort has slipped, asking directly about what they need — more space, more reassurance, a slower pace, a conversation with someone outside the relationship — usually helps. The harder version is somebody who has begun to disengage emotionally while keeping the structure intact. Watch where their genuine ease shows up. Real Four of Wands feeling is unmistakable when it is present, and noticeable when it has gone missing.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel comfortable, warm and quietly grateful that you are in their life. Being with you has stopped feeling like a project they have to manage and started feeling like a room they can rest in. They are not anxiously scanning the connection for problems; they are enjoying it, leaning into it, looking around at their wider life and noticing that you make it better. The feeling has a domestic quality even if you are not yet living together — a sense of fitting, of belonging, of being on the same side.\n\nThere is also a happy public dimension to how they feel. They want to bring you closer to the people and traditions that matter to them, not to test you but because they are pleased that you exist. Expect introductions, invitations, small inclusions that say more than declarations would. Their feelings are settled, joyful and rooted. They are picturing more of you in their everyday life, and that picture is making them smile when no one is watching.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Four of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Four of Wands as feelings is one of the most heartwarming cards in the deck. It describes attraction that has matured into genuine comfort and belonging. The other person feels at home with you, proud to be connected to you, and ready to integrate you into their wider life. Expect introductions, milestones and the quiet ease of someone who has decided you are part of the picture they are building. This is settled, joyful, public-facing love — not a passing spark, but a hearth.' },
      { q: 'Does Four of Wands mean commitment?', a: 'Very often, yes. The Four of Wands as feelings frequently coincides with relationship milestones: meeting family, moving in, engagement, marriage or the quieter equivalents of those thresholds. The other person feels ready to mark what you have publicly and privately. They are not just willing to commit; they are excited to do so. If you have been waiting for a sign that the relationship is heading somewhere lasting, this card is among the clearest yeses you can draw.' },
      { q: 'What does Four of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Four of Wands describes warmth that exists but cannot quite settle into ease. They care, but family pressure, timing, internal uncertainty or rushed milestones are making the comfortable version of love hard to inhabit. Often this is repairable — slow the pace, name the friction kindly, give the foundation time to firm up. The card becomes a problem when it is ignored, not when it appears. Treat it as a request to reinforce the hearth before adding another log.' },
      { q: 'Is Four of Wands a sign of marriage?', a: 'It can be, and it is among the most marriage-friendly cards in the deck. The Four of Wands carries the imagery of celebration, community, public commitment and shared joy — many traditions of betrothal and wedding ceremony are visible in its scenery. When it appears as feelings, the other person is often imagining or actively planning the kind of milestone that makes a relationship official. It is not a guarantee of a specific date, but it is a strong indication that the trajectory is heading toward something celebratory and serious.' },
    ],
  },

  'five-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Five of Wands as feelings describes attraction tangled with friction. The other person feels something for you — Wands always carry heat — but the heat is currently expressing itself through conflict, competition or chaotic mixed signals rather than steady warmth. They may pick small fights, tease too hard, compete with you in ways that feel pointed, or surround your connection with so much noise that the underlying feeling is hard to hear. The flame is real; the household around it is loud.\n\nThis card sometimes shows up when there are simply too many competing voices in the picture. They may be juggling more than one romantic interest, navigating disapproval from friends or family, or struggling internally with parts of themselves that disagree about what they want. The result is a person who feels drawn to you in one breath and dismissive in the next, warm on Tuesday and combative on Thursday. It is rarely cruel; it is more that the inner chorus has not agreed on a single position yet.\n\nThe other meaning is genuine rivalry. They may see you as a worthy match — intellectually, physically, romantically — and the way they express attraction is to spar with you. Some people flirt by agreeing; others flirt by challenging. If your dynamic has always carried a competitive charge that both of you enjoy, the Five of Wands is honouring that as authentic feeling. The work is to keep the friction generative rather than draining, and to notice when you are still wanted underneath all the noise.`,
    reversedLong: `The Five of Wands reversed as feelings describes the end of friction — for better or worse. The healthier reading is that they have stopped picking unnecessary fights with you and are letting the genuine attraction underneath the noise come forward. The constant testing, the petty disagreements, the dramatic flare-ups that defined an earlier phase are quieting down, and what remains feels more like real desire and less like exhausting performance.\n\nThe less healthy reading is that they have stopped engaging because they have stopped caring. Wands fight when they care; when they no longer do, they go quiet. If they used to spar with you and now their replies are bland, brief or absent, the Five reversed may be telling you that the heat which fuelled the conflict has cooled, and what looks like peace is actually disinterest in disguise. This is uncomfortable to consider, but worth holding alongside the kinder reading.\n\nA third version of this reversal is somebody who is privately stepping back from competition with you that they had been quietly losing. Perhaps they were one of several pursuers, or perhaps they were chasing your attention while you were already partnered, and they have decided not to fight that battle any longer. Their feelings may still be present, but they have chosen restraint. Read the surrounding cards to tell which of these is happening. The Five of Wands reversed often clarifies fast: within a few weeks, you usually know whether peace was the start of real warmth or the polite cover on a fading interest.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel attracted to you, but their attraction is coming out sideways. They may be teasing more than complimenting, competing more than collaborating, picking small fights when what they actually want is closeness. The fire is genuine; the channel is messy. If you have been confused by mixed signals, this card is your explanation. They are not playing games on purpose; they are caught between conflicting parts of themselves that have not yet agreed on how to approach you.\n\nThere is also a chance that they enjoy the friction itself. Some people flirt through challenge, and what looks like conflict from the outside is actually their preferred form of intimacy. If your dynamic has always had a competitive edge that you both seemed to like, that is the Five of Wands honouring real feeling in an unusual costume. Either way, expect more chaos than calm from them right now. The feelings are present and warm; they are simply travelling through a noisy room before they reach you.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Five of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Five of Wands as feelings describes attraction tangled with friction. The other person feels something real for you, but the feeling is expressing itself through conflict, teasing, mixed signals or competing voices in their life rather than clean warmth. The fire is genuine; the household around it is loud. Sometimes the friction is flirtation in disguise; sometimes it is genuine indecision among rivals or unresolved inner parts. Read the dynamic honestly. Their interest is present, just not yet arriving cleanly.' },
      { q: 'Are mixed signals always Five of Wands?', a: 'Often, yes. The Five of Wands is one of the classic mixed-signals cards in feelings readings. It describes someone whose attraction is real but whose expression of it is chaotic — hot one day, dismissive the next, eager then competitive. The mix is not usually strategic; it is genuine internal conflict spilling outward. If you keep drawing this card around a particular person, the kindest move is to stop trying to interpret each individual signal and instead watch the overall pattern over several weeks. Patterns tell the truth.' },
      { q: 'What does Five of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Five of Wands shows friction lifting. The kind version is that genuine attraction is finally coming forward without the noise — fewer fights, less testing, more clean warmth. The harder version is that the friction stopped because the feeling did, and what looks like peace is actually disengagement. Surrounding cards usually clarify which is which. Watch the next few weeks. If real interest is there, it expresses itself clearly once the static drops. If it was the static, silence will keep growing.' },
      { q: 'Does Five of Wands mean they are choosing between me and someone else?', a: 'Sometimes, yes. The Five of Wands can describe a literal love triangle or shortlist — the other person is genuinely interested in you but also juggling another connection (or several) and has not yet decided. It can also describe inner rivalry: parts of themselves arguing about whether to pursue you. Either way, the energy is unsettled. The card itself does not predict which way they will choose, but it tells you the choice is currently active. Time and patience usually reveal the outcome faster than any direct confrontation will.' },
    ],
  },

  'six-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Six of Wands as feelings describes someone who is proud to be associated with you. Their attraction has a public, celebratory quality — they want to be seen with you, want their friends to meet you, want to praise you out loud rather than keep their interest quiet. You feel like a win to them, in the most affectionate sense of that word: connection with you boosts their sense of self, brightens their week, and gives them something genuine to look forward to. There is heat here, but the dominant note is admiration.\n\nThis card often appears when one person has been quietly drawing the other out of a more guarded chapter. They may have been single for a long time, recovering from disappointment, or unsure they would meet anyone who genuinely impressed them — and you do. They notice your competence, your charm, your achievements. They feel honoured to have your attention. That honouring tends to come out as praise, generosity and a willingness to champion you to others, sometimes in ways that surprise you with their warmth.\n\nThe deeper feeling is recognition. They see you, and they like what they see, and they are not embarrassed about it. Expect their friends to know your name, their family to be quietly briefed, their social circle to be aware that something significant is happening. Their feelings are warm, confident and unembarrassed. They are not trying to play it cool. They want you, they admire you, and they would rather the people in their life know it than not.`,
    reversedLong: `The Six of Wands reversed as feelings describes attraction complicated by ego dynamics. They may genuinely like you, but the way they express it is being shaped by pride, comparison or competing claims to status. Perhaps they want to be the one being chased rather than the one chasing. Perhaps they keep score, even silently, about who messaged first, who organised the last date, whose career is going better. The warmth is present; it just keeps tripping over their need to feel admired in return.\n\nReversed, this card can also describe somebody who is hiding their feelings because they are not sure you will reciprocate. The Six upright is unembarrassed admiration; reversed, it is admiration that has gone underground out of fear of public rejection. They may be telling friends one thing and you another, or holding back compliments they actually want to give. Their pride is louder than their courage. If you sense this is the situation, gentle reassurance often unlocks more than pressure will — the reversal is sometimes a person waiting for safety, not someone playing games.\n\nA harder version of this reversal is a connection where you are not getting the credit you have been giving. You have been championing them, praising them, lifting them up — and they have been receiving it without quite returning the warmth at the same volume. Their feelings may be real, but the exchange has tipped. The Six of Wands reversed asks you to notice the asymmetry and to stop performing admiration that is not being matched. Real mutual feeling shows up in mutual praise, eventually. If it does not, the imbalance itself is the message.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel impressed by you, and they are not embarrassed about it. You stand out in their mind — for your competence, your warmth, your sense of self — and being connected to you makes them feel slightly luckier than they expected to feel. There is a quiet sense of pride in the way they think about you. They notice when you do something well. They want to tell other people about it. They like the version of themselves they get to be when they are around you.\n\nUnderneath the admiration is genuine romantic feeling, but the admiration is what is most active. Expect compliments, public warmth, introductions to friends, perhaps a tendency to talk you up when you are not in the room. Their feelings are confident, warm and visible. They are choosing to honour you rather than to play it cool, and that choice is itself the message. They want you to know how highly they think of you.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Six of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Six of Wands as feelings describes proud, public, admiring attraction. The other person genuinely likes you and is not interested in hiding it. They speak highly of you, want to be seen with you, and want their wider circle to know that you matter. There is romantic heat here, but the dominant note is admiration — they think you are impressive, and they are honoured you have noticed them back. This is confident, generous love rather than guarded or game-playing love.' },
      { q: 'Does Six of Wands mean they tell friends about me?', a: 'Almost certainly yes. One of the clearest signatures of the Six of Wands as feelings is that the other person is talking about you to the people who matter to them. Their friends know your name. Their family has been told something is happening. Their social circle is aware of you in a way that goes beyond casual mention. This public sharing is part of how they express genuine interest. If you have been wondering whether they are taking the connection seriously, this card is a strong yes.' },
      { q: 'What does Six of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Six of Wands describes attraction complicated by ego or fear of reciprocity. They may keep score, hold back compliments, or hide their feelings because they are not sure you feel the same. The warmth is often real but tangled with pride. Gentle reassurance helps when this is the situation. The harder reading is asymmetry — you are doing more of the admiring than they are. If the imbalance keeps repeating, take it seriously. Mutual feeling shows up in mutual praise eventually.' },
      { q: 'Is Six of Wands a sign of public commitment?', a: 'Often, yes. The Six of Wands as feelings frequently appears when the other person is ready to make the relationship visible — introductions, social media presence, public acknowledgement, eventually relationship milestones. They want the connection witnessed rather than hidden. While it is not as marriage-specific as the Four of Wands, it is a strong indicator that they see no need to keep what you share private and are happy for the wider world to know that they are with you.' },
    ],
  },

  'seven-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Seven of Wands as feelings describes someone who is defending their feelings for you, often against pressure they did not expect. They are attracted, sometimes deeply, but their connection with you is generating opposition — from family who do not approve, from friends who are sceptical, from a previous partner who has not entirely let go, or from their own inner critic who keeps presenting reasons this should not work. They are choosing you anyway, and the choosing itself is becoming part of how they feel.\n\nThis card can also describe someone protecting their position in your life from perceived competition. They may suspect you have other options, or worry that they are not the most impressive candidate in your orbit. Rather than retreat, they are standing their ground. Their feelings show up as steadiness in the face of doubt: they keep showing up, keep returning, keep claiming their place in your week even when circumstances are not making it easy. There is dignity in this kind of attraction.\n\nThe deeper feeling is conviction. They believe what is between you is worth defending, and the defence itself is sharpening their commitment. People often emerge from a Seven of Wands chapter clearer about how much someone matters to them, because the resistance has forced them to articulate it. Trust the persistence. Their feelings are warm, resolute and increasingly certain. They are not running from the difficulty; they are letting it prove to them that you are worth standing for.`,
    reversedLong: `The Seven of Wands reversed as feelings describes someone whose willingness to fight for the connection has begun to falter. They had feelings, perhaps strong ones, but the resistance — from family, ex partners, their own inner doubt, or simply the cumulative cost of defending something difficult — has worn them down. They are still attracted; they are simply less sure they have the energy to keep claiming you against the headwinds.\n\nReversed, this card can also describe somebody who has stopped defending their place because they no longer feel they need to — and not always in a healthy way. Sometimes this means complacency: they assume you are not going anywhere and have stopped putting in the effort that earlier defined them. Sometimes it means resignation: they have decided the obstacles are larger than the feeling, and they are quietly preparing to step back rather than admit it out loud.\n\nThere is a gentler version too. Reversed Seven of Wands can mark the moment somebody finally drops a defensive posture they no longer need. If they have been guarded with you because of past wounds, their walls coming down is a real gift, not a problem — even if the transition feels wobbly. Read the surrounding cards to tell which version is on the table. Burnout asks for rest and reassurance. Resignation asks for honesty. Healing asks for patience and tenderness. The card responds well to whichever conversation you can manage to have without flinching.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel attracted to you and also a little embattled. Something is making this connection harder than they expected — family pressure, a complicated personal situation, doubts they are still working through — and yet they are not walking away. If anything, the resistance is clarifying how much you matter to them. They are choosing you on purpose, sometimes daily, sometimes against their own anxious second-guessing, and that choice is itself a love language.\n\nWhat they may not say outright is how much energy this is costing them. They want to come across as confident and steady, but inside they are working hard to stay the course. Patience, reassurance and visible loyalty from your side mean a great deal here. Their feelings are real, resolute and somewhat tender. They need to feel that you are worth the trouble — and a little softness from you will go a long way to confirming that they are right.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Seven of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Seven of Wands as feelings describes attraction that is being defended. The other person is genuinely interested in you, but their connection with you is meeting resistance — from family, exes, their own doubts, or competition — and they are choosing to hold their ground anyway. The card honours their persistence. Their feelings are real, sometimes intensified by the very difficulty of expressing them. They are standing up for what they want, and that standing is becoming part of how they love.' },
      { q: 'Does Seven of Wands mean they are fighting for me?', a: 'Often, yes. The Seven of Wands as feelings frequently describes someone who is actively choosing the connection in the face of obstacles. That might be disapproving family, a difficult ex situation, distance, scheduling, or just the cumulative effort it takes to make something work in a busy life. They are willing to put in the effort. Their feelings are not casual; they are committed enough to defend their place in your week against whatever is trying to push them out of it.' },
      { q: 'What does Seven of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Seven of Wands describes defensive energy that has begun to wobble. They may be tired of fighting for the connection, complacent now that they feel secure, or genuinely lowering walls they no longer need. The reading depends on context. If they have grown distant, it is often burnout or resignation. If they have grown softer, it can be healing. Surrounding cards usually clarify which is happening. The card responds well to honest conversation in any of those scenarios.' },
      { q: 'Is Seven of Wands a sign they are committed?', a: 'It is often a sign they are committing actively, in real time, against real opposition. That is a stronger signal than commitment expressed in easy conditions, because it has been tested. The Seven of Wands honours people who keep showing up when staying would be easier to abandon. If you have been wondering whether the other person is serious, this card is a strong yes — provided you can return the loyalty they are extending. They need to feel that the fight is worth their while.' },
    ],
  },

  'eight-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Eight of Wands as feelings describes attraction in fast-forward. The other person feels something for you and they are not slow-walking it. Messages arrive quickly. Plans accelerate. The connection that started gently last week has, somehow, picked up momentum, and they are happily riding it rather than trying to slow it down. This is honest, eager, communicative feeling — the kind that makes its presence known loudly and often.\n\nThis card often shows up when communication has suddenly opened up between two people. A previously quiet text thread becomes lively. A long-distance flirtation finally agrees on dates. Someone you have been wondering about reaches out at last, and the conversation flows easily once it starts. Eight of Wands feelings travel — through screens, across distances, through delayed circumstances that finally clear. Whatever was suspended is now moving.\n\nThe deeper feeling is excitement that wants to share itself. They are not playing hard to get; they are showing up. Expect their attention to be visible in the small daily things — the morning message, the article they thought of you when they saw, the spontaneous video call — as well as in faster movement toward bigger commitments like meeting, travelling, or defining what this is. Their feelings are quick, warm and confident. They have decided to lean in, and they are hoping you will lean in too.`,
    reversedLong: `The Eight of Wands reversed as feelings describes a connection that has lost momentum. Where the upright card flies, this one drifts. Messages slow down. Replies arrive later or not at all. The easy back-and-forth that used to define your dynamic has thinned into something more uncertain. Their feelings may still be present, but the speed and ease with which they were expressing them has clearly changed.\n\nReversed, this card sometimes describes a person whose attention has been pulled elsewhere — work crisis, family demands, an old situation that has resurfaced — and who simply has less to give right now. Their warmth toward you has not necessarily disappeared; their bandwidth has. Other times the slowdown is more pointed. They have cooled on the connection without saying so directly, and the silence is doing the talking they are not yet willing to do themselves.\n\nA third version of this reversal is somebody who moved too fast and has now pulled back to recover their balance. The early days were intense — perhaps more intense than they were ready for — and they are quietly trying to bring the temperature down to a level they can sustain. This is not necessarily a rejection; it is often a request for a slower pace. Read their actions, not their explanations. If real feeling is there, the silence eventually breaks. If it does not, the breakdown of communication is itself the message, and you are entitled to redirect your fire elsewhere.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel excited and forward-leaning about you. The connection has caught fire in a way they are happy to let move quickly, and they are expressing it through speed and frequency: more messages, faster replies, plans that materialise instead of staying theoretical. They like the pace. They want to keep talking, keep meeting, keep building the small daily intimacy that fast communication produces. There is nothing aloof about how they are showing up.\n\nWhat they may not say outright is how much they are enjoying this. People with the Eight of Wands around them tend to feel a kind of giddy momentum — like something is finally happening after a long quiet period, or like the connection has unlocked a part of them they had almost forgotten. Their feelings are quick, communicative and visibly happy. Whatever has been held back is now arriving, and they are hoping you are receiving the signal at the speed they are sending it.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Eight of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Eight of Wands as feelings describes fast, communicative attraction. The other person is excited about you and showing it through the speed and frequency of their attention. Messages arrive quickly, plans accelerate, momentum builds. They are not playing it cool or stretching out the conversation; they are leaning in. This is honest, eager, forward-leaning feeling — the kind that makes itself known loudly and often, and that wants you to lean in with the same energy.' },
      { q: 'Does Eight of Wands mean they will reach out?', a: 'Very often, yes. The Eight of Wands is among the most reliable contact cards in feelings readings. When it appears, expect a message, a call, a sudden re-emergence in your inbox — sometimes from someone who had gone quiet, sometimes from a new connection moving quickly. The card describes communication in flight. If you have been waiting to hear from someone, drawing this card means the wait is usually short. They want to talk to you, and they are about to act on it.' },
      { q: 'What does Eight of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Eight of Wands describes communication that has stalled. Messages slow down, replies get vaguer, and the easy momentum the upright card promised has dropped. Sometimes this is bandwidth (life got busy), sometimes it is cooling interest, and sometimes it is somebody who moved too fast and has stepped back to recover their balance. Watch actions over the next few weeks. Real feeling restores its own pace eventually. Sustained silence usually means the connection has changed shape.' },
      { q: 'Is Eight of Wands a sign of love at first sight?', a: 'It can be. The Eight of Wands often describes attraction that moves astonishingly fast — the first conversation that lasts hours, the first date that turns into the next three weekends, the connection that overrides the usual pacing rules. Whether that fast start grows into something lasting depends on what you build after the rush. The card honours the genuine heat of the early days without making promises about duration. Enjoy the momentum; let what comes next show you what it is.' },
    ],
  },

  'nine-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Nine of Wands as feelings describes attraction that has had to survive something. The other person feels something real for you, but they have arrived at you carrying scars — from previous relationships, family wounds, betrayals that taught them to brace before opening — and their feelings come paired with a certain wariness. They want to trust you; they are also, quietly, on guard. The fire is real; the watchman has not entirely gone off duty.\n\nThis card often shows up around people who have been hurt before and are trying not to be hurt again. They may take longer than you would like to define the relationship, hesitate before introducing you to important people in their life, or pull back briefly after moments of unexpected closeness. None of this is necessarily about you. It is about a nervous system that learned, somewhere along the way, that intimacy comes with risk. They are choosing you anyway, but they need the choosing to feel safe enough to sustain.\n\nThe deeper feeling is durable loyalty earned through difficulty. Once a Nine of Wands person commits, they tend to stay. Their love has had to fight to exist, and that fighting has made it less casual than most. Trust the steady pattern over the wobbly individual moments. Their feelings are warm, brave and slightly bruised. They are quietly hoping you will be the partner who finally lets the watchman get some sleep, and gentleness from you — repeated, reliable, unembellished — does more here than any grand gesture could.`,
    reversedLong: `The Nine of Wands reversed as feelings describes a defensive posture that has begun to give way — either healthily or unsustainably. The healthier version is someone whose walls are finally coming down with you. The bracing they have done since previous hurts is softening. They are letting themselves be seen, letting themselves trust, taking the risk of believing this might be different. That transition is tender. Expect them to feel exposed, sometimes irritable, sometimes more emotional than usual, as they unlearn long-standing habits of guardedness.\n\nThe less healthy version is somebody whose nervous system has tipped from cautious into paranoid. They are seeing threats that are not there, attributing motives to you that you do not have, exhausting themselves and you with reassurances that never quite stick. Their feelings may still be present, but their fear is louder than their trust. This is rarely about your behaviour; it is the unresolved past walking into the present. Compassion helps, but compassion without limits can become its own kind of exhaustion.\n\nA third reading is plain burnout. They have been guarding their heart for so long that they no longer have the energy to even mount the defence — and you may be receiving the version of them that is too tired to either close or fully open. Patience and slowness help here, but so does honesty about what you yourself can sustain. The Nine of Wands reversed responds to deliberate, mutual tenderness over time. It does not respond to either side performing fine when they are not.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel drawn to you and also a little guarded. They want to trust you; their history is making it harder than they would like. You will see flashes of real warmth — long conversations, vulnerable moments, plans that suggest they are taking this seriously — followed sometimes by quieter days when they retreat slightly to check that they are still safe. The retreats are rarely about you. They are about a part of them that learned, long before you arrived, that closeness can be costly.\n\nWhat they may not say outright is how much it means that you keep showing up steadily. Reliability is the love language they respond to most. Every time you do what you said you would, every time you stay calm in a small disagreement, every time you treat them with consistent kindness, a layer of their armour quietly thins. Their feelings are warm, brave and a little tired. They are choosing you, again and again, and they need the version of you that makes that choice feel safe.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Nine of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Nine of Wands as feelings describes attraction shaped by past hurt. The other person genuinely feels something for you, but they carry scars from previous relationships, family wounds or betrayals that have taught them to brace. Their feelings come paired with a quiet vigilance. They want to trust; they are working at it. Patience, consistency and steady kindness mean far more to this person than grand gestures. Once they decide you are safe, they tend to love loyally and well.' },
      { q: 'Does Nine of Wands mean they have trust issues?', a: 'Often, yes. The Nine of Wands as feelings frequently describes someone who has learned to guard their heart and is taking longer than average to lower the watchman. This is rarely about you specifically; it is about what their nervous system learned in earlier relationships or formative experiences. The card asks for understanding rather than pressure. Trust is rebuilt by repetition — small reliable acts, kept promises, calm responses to small frictions — much more than by reassurance offered in single big moments.' },
      { q: 'What does Nine of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Nine of Wands describes walls beginning to come down — sometimes healthily, sometimes wobbly. The healthier version is real healing: they are letting you in despite old habits of guardedness. The harder version is paranoia or burnout, where their fear has outrun the present situation. Read context carefully. Slowness and consistency from you help in either case, but be honest with yourself about what you can sustainably give. Mutual tenderness, not one-sided effort, is what restores trust here.' },
      { q: 'Is Nine of Wands a sign of lasting love?', a: 'It can be, and often is. Once the Nine of Wands person decides they are safe with you, they tend to be among the most loyal partners in the deck. Their love has had to fight to exist, which makes it less casual and more durable than most. The card asks for patience and reliability through the wary phase, and rewards both. If you can outlast the watchman, you usually get to meet the deeply committed person on the other side.' },
    ],
  },

  'ten-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Ten of Wands as feelings describes someone who cares about you but is overwhelmed. They feel something real — there is genuine warmth in the picture — but their life is currently carrying so much that the connection with you is one more thing on a back too full to bend. Work pressure, family responsibility, financial strain, mental load, the cumulative weight of obligations they cannot easily put down: all of this is competing for the energy they would otherwise spend on you.\n\nThis card often shows up in relationships where one or both partners are running close to burnout. Their messages may be shorter than they used to be, their planning more reactive, their emotional bandwidth thinner. They are not pulling away because they have stopped feeling. They are pulling away because they have stopped having anything left to give by the time they get to you. This is sometimes harder to read than indifference, because the love is still there underneath; it is simply buried under load.\n\nThe deeper feeling is loyalty under strain. They want to be there for you, want to be a better partner than they are currently managing to be, and they often feel guilty about the gap between intention and reality. Compassion helps. Pressure does not. The most useful thing you can offer a Ten of Wands person is small, generous reduction of their burden where you can, and patience while they work out what they can sustainably carry. Their feelings are warm, real and slightly buried. Lighten the load, and the connection underneath usually re-emerges intact.`,
    reversedLong: `The Ten of Wands reversed as feelings describes either burden being released — finally — or burden that has been carried until something has broken. The healthier version is somebody who is at last putting down what they did not need to carry. They are saying no to commitments that were draining them, delegating tasks, asking for help, and rediscovering the energy they have for you in the process. The connection may have felt thin during the loaded chapter, but it is reviving as their bandwidth returns.\n\nThe less healthy version is collapse. They carried too much for too long and have hit a wall — emotional shutdown, physical exhaustion, depressive withdrawal, or simply the kind of irritable depletion that strains every connection in their life including yours. Their feelings for you may still be present, but they are not currently accessible. This is not punishment; it is a system that has run out of fuel. Patience helps. So does naming the reality rather than pretending everything is fine.\n\nA third reading is somebody who has finally let a relationship go because they recognised it was contributing to their overload — perhaps a previous partner, an ex who kept reappearing, an obligation they had been pretending was fine. If this is the picture, the reversed Ten of Wands is good news for you indirectly: they are clearing space, and what they make room for next tends to be lighter, healthier and more sustainable. Watch their pattern over the coming weeks. As load lifts, capacity for genuine connection usually returns with it.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel something for you, but they are exhausted. Life is asking more of them than they have to give, and the connection with you is competing with a stack of obligations that feels barely manageable. They want to show up better than they are. They notice the gap between what they wish they could offer and what they actually have the energy to offer, and the gap is making them quietly hard on themselves. The feelings are there; the bandwidth is not.\n\nWhat they may not say outright is how grateful they would be for understanding rather than pressure. Small acts of generosity from you — a no-stakes invitation, a message that does not require a long reply, an explicit "I see you are tired" — mean more here than passionate declarations would. Their feelings are warm, real and currently buried under load. Lighten the weight, and the connection underneath usually returns intact. Push for more than they have, and the warmth keeps retreating to protect what little is left.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Ten of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Ten of Wands as feelings describes care buried under overwhelm. The other person feels something for you, but their life is currently carrying so much that the connection is competing with a stack of obligations. They are not pulling away because they have stopped feeling. They are pulling away because they have run out of energy by the time they get to you. Compassion and small acts of generosity help. Pressure does not. The warmth is real; the bandwidth is thin.' },
      { q: 'Does Ten of Wands mean they are too busy for me?', a: 'Often, yes — but the busyness is not strategic. It is genuine, and it is costing them. The Ten of Wands as feelings describes someone whose to-do list and emotional load are outrunning their capacity, and you are feeling the downstream effect. They wish they could show up better. They notice the gap. The most useful response is usually patience, low-stakes contact and explicit acknowledgement that you can see what they are carrying. That recognition does more for them than another evening of trying to perform fine.' },
      { q: 'What does Ten of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Ten of Wands describes burden either being released or having caused collapse. If they are putting down what was overloading them, capacity for connection returns and the relationship usually revives. If they have broken under the weight, their feelings may still be present but currently inaccessible. Either way, the card asks for honesty about reality and patience while load redistributes. As burden lifts, the warmth underneath the exhaustion tends to return intact.' },
      { q: 'Is Ten of Wands a sign they will leave?', a: 'Not usually — it is more often a sign they need help redistributing what they are carrying. The Ten of Wands is exhaustion, not exit. Most relationships under this card recover well once the overload is named and addressed. Where things go wrong is when the exhausted partner pretends to be fine for too long, or when the other partner pressures for more than is sustainable. Lighten the load together where you can, and the connection usually outlasts the chapter that strained it.' },
    ],
  },

  'page-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Page of Wands as feelings describes attraction in its most playful, curious form. The other person is excited about you — sometimes obviously so — and their interest comes with a kind of boyish or girlish energy regardless of their actual age. They want to know what makes you laugh, what you are passionate about, where you would travel, what you are working on. Their messages tend to be enthusiastic, sometimes scattered, often longer than necessary because they are simply enjoying the conversation. There is heat here, but the dominant note is exploration.\n\nThis card often describes someone in the early discovery phase of a connection: they have not yet decided what this is, but they like finding out. They may flirt easily, make spontaneous suggestions, share creative projects or new interests with you, and generally bring a quality of "let's see what happens" to your dynamic. Page of Wands feelings are not always built for endurance, but they are unmistakably authentic in the moment. You are an adventure they are happily setting out on.\n\nThe deeper feeling is delight. They like who they get to be around you. Conversations with you give them ideas. Time with you energises rather than drains them, and they want more of it without quite knowing yet what shape "more" should take. Trust the playfulness without rushing past it. Their feelings are warm, inquisitive and full of spark. Let them explore at their own pace — Pages bloom into Knights when they feel safe to keep adventuring, and crushed when they are pushed to declare more than they are ready to.`,
    reversedLong: `The Page of Wands reversed as feelings describes enthusiasm that is either inconsistent or unfocused. They may be genuinely interested in you, but their attention scatters easily — to other people, new projects, the next shiny distraction — and you find yourself struggling to anchor their consistent presence. The fire is real; it is also, currently, undisciplined. One week they are messaging constantly; the next, they have gone quiet in pursuit of something else.\n\nReversed, this card can also describe someone whose feelings are immature for the relationship you actually want. They like the idea of you, the chase of you, the early flirtation — but they are not yet ready or willing to handle the responsibilities of deeper connection. Their interest tends to evaporate as soon as the relationship asks anything serious of them. This is not always a character flaw; sometimes it is genuine emotional age, and the only honest move is to read it accurately and adjust your expectations.\n\nA third reading is somebody whose enthusiasm has been blocked or discouraged — by their own anxiety, by a previous rejection, by uncertainty about whether you reciprocate. They like you more than they are letting on, but they have pulled in their natural spark out of fear of looking foolish. Gentle encouragement helps here, though it is wise to let them find their own courage rather than do it for them. Read the surrounding cards. Scatter, immaturity and shyness all look similar at first glance, and the right response to each is different.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel curious about you and a little fascinated. You are interesting to them in a way they did not entirely expect — your sense of humour, the way you talk about what you love, the small details that other people might miss but that they have already noticed. Conversations with you give them energy. They walk away from your meetings feeling lit up rather than depleted, and they are quietly trying to figure out how to spend more time in your orbit without making it weird.\n\nWhat they may not say outright is how playful you make them feel. People with the Page of Wands around them often find themselves more imaginative, more willing to make jokes, more willing to be slightly ridiculous than they usually allow themselves to be. That is a real form of attraction, even if it does not look like the brooding intensity some people associate with serious love. Their feelings are warm, sparkly and exploratory. They are enjoying you. Let them keep enjoying.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Page of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Page of Wands as feelings describes playful, curious attraction in its discovery phase. The other person is excited about you and showing it through enthusiastic messages, spontaneous ideas and a clear delight in your company. They have not necessarily decided what this is yet, but they are enjoying finding out. The card honours real feeling that has not yet had time to declare itself with seriousness. Let them explore. Pages mature into Knights when given room to keep adventuring at their own pace.' },
      { q: 'Does Page of Wands mean they have a crush on me?', a: 'Yes, often a fairly obvious one. The Page of Wands as feelings is among the clearest crush cards in the deck. The other person is excited by you, talks about you to friends, finds reasons to spend time with you, and brings a quality of playful curiosity to your interactions. Their feelings are real and warm, even if they have not yet matured into something more serious. Enjoy the spark. Crushes that arrive with this card often grow into deeper connection when given a little time and gentle handling.' },
      { q: 'What does Page of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Page of Wands describes enthusiasm that has become inconsistent or unfocused. They may be genuinely interested but easily distracted, emotionally immature for what you want, or holding back from shyness. Surrounding cards usually clarify which. The fire is present; the discipline is missing. Adjust your expectations rather than performing the relationship harder. If the spark is real and the immaturity is the issue, time may resolve it. If the scatter is character-deep, honesty about the mismatch is the kindest move.' },
      { q: 'Is Page of Wands a sign of new love?', a: 'Frequently, yes. The Page of Wands is a classic herald of a fresh, exciting connection — often someone younger in spirit, sometimes younger in age, who brings playful and curious energy into your life. The card honours the early days when nothing is defined yet and everything feels possible. Whether the spark develops into a lasting relationship depends on what you build after the initial flirtation, but the present feeling is unmistakably real and worth enjoying without too much premature pressure.' },
    ],
  },

  'knight-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Knight of Wands as feelings describes attraction that is bold, fast and unmistakable. The other person is fired up about you and not interested in being subtle about it. They make their interest known clearly — through messages, gestures, plans, sometimes through unexpected grand moves that surprise you with their intensity. There is real desire in the picture, and they would rather risk overshooting than be polite about it. The chase is on, and they are enjoying it.\n\nThis card often describes someone who has decided you are worth pursuing and is going to do so with whatever they have. Expect spontaneity: weekend trips proposed on a Tuesday, surprise visits, big ideas about your future together that arrive before you have agreed on anything. The Knight is not pacing themselves. They feel something, and they want to act on it now, while the energy is high. This can be exhilarating, especially if you have come from quieter or more guarded connections.\n\nThe honest caveat is that Knights of Wands burn hot and sometimes burn fast. The same impulsiveness that makes them thrilling at the start can make them inconsistent later, especially if the relationship asks them to settle into routine before they have worked out how to do that. Their feelings, at this moment, are entirely genuine. Whether they sustain depends on whether the heat learns how to become a steady hearth. Enjoy the gallop; just notice whether they can also walk, when the road eventually requires walking.`,
    reversedLong: `The Knight of Wands reversed as feelings describes someone whose passion has gone unreliable. They had feelings for you, often intense ones, but their willingness to follow through has become spotty. Plans get made and broken. Promises are sincere in the moment and forgotten by the weekend. The heat is real when it appears, but its appearances are becoming harder to predict, and you may be left wondering whether to count on them at all.\n\nReversed, this card can describe someone who burns out of their own infatuations quickly. They love the chase; they struggle with the settling. As soon as the relationship asks for consistency rather than excitement, their attention starts wandering — sometimes to other people, sometimes to other projects, sometimes simply back into themselves. Their feelings are not necessarily fake. They are just structurally short. They mean what they say when they say it, and then they move.\n\nA different version of this reversal is somebody whose fire has been temporarily dampened by frustration, anger or feeling controlled. They want you, but something in the dynamic has them stalling rather than charging. Reading the surrounding cards usually clarifies whether you are dealing with chronic inconsistency or a passing slump. The first asks for honest acceptance of who they are. The second responds to a single direct conversation that releases whatever has been blocking the gallop. Either way, trust their pattern over their declarations. Knights reveal themselves in what they actually do, not in what they promise mid-flight.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel fired up about you and ready to act on it. They are not in the mood to play coy or stretch out the courtship. They want to see you, take you somewhere, make something happen between you — and they are likely to express that through bold gestures rather than careful words. The intensity may surprise you. It may also surprise them, but they are not slowing down to analyse it.\n\nWhat they may not say outright is how vital you are making them feel. The Knight of Wands person tends to come alive when they are pursuing someone they are genuinely excited about. You are tapping into a part of them that has been waiting for a worthy reason to gallop, and they are happily letting themselves go. Their feelings are loud, warm and confident. Enjoy the ride. Just notice whether they can also be present when the gallop slows, because that is the eventual test that decides whether the heat becomes a relationship or remains a brilliant chapter.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Knight of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Knight of Wands as feelings describes bold, fast, openly expressed attraction. The other person is fired up about you and not interested in being subtle about it. They pursue you with energy, make plans quickly, and bring grand-gesture energy to the connection. Their feelings are real and intense in the moment. The honest caveat is that Knights burn hot and sometimes burn fast — the test is whether their heat can later learn to become a steady hearth, not just an exciting gallop.' },
      { q: 'Does Knight of Wands mean they want a fling?', a: 'Sometimes, yes — but not always. The Knight of Wands as feelings describes someone whose default mode is intensity, which can either grow into a lasting partnership or burn out as a brief, brilliant chapter. The card itself does not predict which one. What it tells you is that the present feeling is genuine and the present pace is fast. Watch what they do when the relationship asks for steadiness rather than spectacle. Their answer to that question is your real answer.' },
      { q: 'What does Knight of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Knight of Wands describes passion that has gone unreliable. Plans get broken, intensity comes and goes, follow-through is patchy. The feelings can be real in any individual moment but structurally short. Some Knights reversed are temporarily frustrated and recover with one honest conversation. Others are chronically inconsistent and will keep repeating the same pattern. Trust their behaviour over time, not their declarations mid-gallop. Knights reveal themselves in what they actually sustain.' },
      { q: 'Is Knight of Wands a sign of true love?', a: 'It can be the beginning of one, but rarely the whole story by itself. The Knight of Wands describes the chase phase of love — exciting, intense, fast — which is real and important but not yet a complete picture of partnership. True love often requires the Knight to grow into something steadier over time: the same passion, but with reliability added. If your Knight can make that transition, the connection has every chance of lasting. If they cannot, you may have to enjoy what was given without expecting it to settle.' },
    ],
  },

  'queen-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The Queen of Wands as feelings describes attraction that is warm, magnetic and unmistakably confident. The other person feels something for you and they are not hiding it — but unlike the Knight, their expression has poise. They radiate rather than chase. Their warmth toward you shows up in steady attention, generous compliments, an easy ability to make you feel both desired and respected. There is heat here, and there is dignity, and the combination is what makes this card such a heartwarming feelings draw.\n\nThis card often describes someone who is comfortable in their own life and choosing to make room for you within it. They are not desperate for your attention; they have plenty of their own. Their interest in you is therefore a real compliment rather than a default — they have options, and they are picking you on purpose. Expect their feelings to come through as confident affection: clear plans, generous time, public warmth, a kind of glow they extend toward you that draws other people in as well.\n\nThe deeper feeling is admiration paired with desire. They find you attractive, but they also genuinely like who you are, and they enjoy bringing you into the warmer parts of their life. Their friends will hear about you. Their family may meet you. Their world is large enough to include you without losing its own shape, and they are happy to make the introduction. Their feelings are loyal, expressive and grounded. They tend to love with their whole presence, not in fragments, and what they offer is real.`,
    reversedLong: `The Queen of Wands reversed as feelings describes warmth that has gone uneven — sometimes generous, sometimes jealous, sometimes withdrawn into self-protection. The other person still feels something for you, but their confidence in the connection has wobbled, and the wobble is producing reactions that do not match their better self. They may compare themselves unfavourably to people in your life, sulk over imagined slights, or grow more controlling than they want to be because insecurity has temporarily edged out trust.\n\nReversed, this card can also describe someone whose natural charisma has been turned against the relationship. They may be flirting visibly with others, drawing attention they do not need, or running a low-grade competition for status that you did not sign up to participate in. The fire is still there; the warmth has tipped into something sharper. This is usually not malice. It is more often a Queen who has lost touch with her own grounded confidence and is performing security she does not currently feel.\n\nA third reading is the Queen who has been hurt and is now withholding her warmth. She has every reason to want to draw closer, but past wounds — or recent ones in this relationship — have made her step back from her natural generosity. Her feelings remain, but she is being careful with them. Read the surrounding cards to tell which version is operating. Insecurity asks for reassurance. Charisma misuse asks for honest conversation about boundaries. Withholding asks for the patience to make the connection feel safe again. The Queen reversed responds to deliberate, respectful tenderness from anyone willing to extend it.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel warmly drawn to you and confident in the warmth. They are not playing coy. They are not pretending to be more interested than they are. They have decided that they like you, and they are happy to show it through generous attention, steady plans and the kind of relaxed affection that does not need constant reassurance. Around you they tend to feel charismatic, alive and at ease — and that combination is part of why being near you is becoming important to them.\n\nWhat they may not say outright is how much they admire who you are. People with the Queen of Wands around them often feel both desired and respected, and that mixture is precisely what this person is extending. Expect compliments that go beyond appearance, introductions to the people in their life who matter, an easy public warmth that does not feel performed. Their feelings are loyal, expressive and grounded. They are choosing you with their whole presence, and they want you to feel it without having to wonder.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does Queen of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The Queen of Wands as feelings describes warm, confident, openly expressed attraction. The other person feels drawn to you and has the poise to show it without games. Their interest comes with admiration as well as desire — they like who you are, not only how you make them feel. Expect generous attention, public warmth, introductions to their wider circle. This is loyal, charismatic, grounded love. They are picking you on purpose, from a place of fullness rather than need, and that choice is part of the compliment.' },
      { q: 'Does Queen of Wands mean they are confident in our connection?', a: 'Very much so. The Queen of Wands as feelings describes someone who is comfortable enough in their own life to extend genuine warmth to yours. They are not desperate, not anxious, not constantly seeking reassurance. Their interest in you sits inside a wider sense of self that is intact. That confidence tends to feel relaxing to be near — they bring ease into the connection rather than tension. If you have been wondering whether you are dating someone secure, this card is a strong yes.' },
      { q: 'What does Queen of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the Queen of Wands describes warmth that has gone uneven — sometimes generous, sometimes insecure, sometimes withholding. Real feeling is still in the picture, but confidence has wobbled. Insecurity, jealousy, charisma misused or a hurt that has caused withdrawal can each produce this reversal. Reading context helps. The card responds to grounded reassurance and respectful boundaries. Most Queen of Wands reversed dynamics recover well once the underlying confidence is rebuilt on both sides.' },
      { q: 'Is Queen of Wands a sign of lasting love?', a: 'Often, yes. The Queen of Wands as feelings describes love that has both passion and dignity — heat that has not collapsed into chaos, generosity that has not become self-erasure. When she chooses someone, she tends to do so for the long haul, and her warmth has the durability of confidence rather than the fragility of infatuation. If you have drawn this card around a particular person, you are most likely dealing with somebody capable of sustained, grown-up love. Receive it without needing to test it.' },
    ],
  },

  'king-of-wands': {
    uprightLong: `The King of Wands as feelings describes attraction that is mature, decisive and openly directed. The other person feels something for you and they have decided to act on it on purpose. Their interest is not impulsive in the way the Knight's would be, nor exploratory in the way the Page's would be. It is purposeful. They have looked at you, considered what they want, and chosen to pursue connection with the clarity of someone who knows how to lead.\n\nThis card often describes someone who has lived enough life to recognise the value of what is in front of them. They are not playing games. They do not need to. They are confident in their own world — their work, their friendships, their sense of themselves — and they want you in it because they think you are exceptional, not because they are lonely. Expect their interest to show up as deliberate action: clear invitations, generous plans, the willingness to take the lead when the moment requires it. They will tell you, in words and gestures, what they think of you.\n\nThe deeper feeling is admiration that has settled into devotion. The King of Wands respects you, and his respect is part of how he loves. He is not the kind to perform feelings he does not feel, nor to hide feelings he has decided to give. What he offers, he tends to mean. His feelings are warm, focused and entirely uninterested in keeping score. He has chosen you, he wants you to know it, and he is committed to acting on that choice consistently rather than dramatically. Receive the steadiness as the love it is.`,
    reversedLong: `The King of Wands reversed as feelings describes maturity that has tipped into something harder. The other person may genuinely care for you, but their leadership has become controlling, their confidence has thickened into arrogance, or their decisiveness has stopped consulting you about decisions that affect you both. The fire is real; the channel has narrowed. What used to feel like strong, generous direction has begun to feel like someone making the relationship's choices on your behalf.\n\nReversed, this card can also describe someone whose private feelings outrun what they are willing to show. They love, perhaps deeply, but pride or fear of vulnerability is keeping them from expressing it as openly as they once did. They communicate through provision rather than affection, through steady presence rather than warm words, and you may find yourself wondering whether their inner experience matches what you are receiving. Often it does. They simply have not figured out how to let the warmth visible while staying in the role they have built for themselves.\n\nA third reading is the King who has been wounded and has retreated into his work, his ambition or his public persona to avoid feeling what is harder. His feelings for you remain, but he is currently unreachable underneath them. This is rarely about you; it is about a man who has been taught that emotions are weakness and is now trying to manage the connection without using any of them. Patience and the refusal to compete with his armour usually help more than direct challenge. The King reversed responds best to people who can wait without losing themselves while he finds his way back to softness.`,
    howTheyFeel: `Right now they feel certain about you, and the certainty is making them act with unusual clarity. They have decided that you matter, and they are organising their attention around that decision. Expect deliberate plans, generous gestures, a willingness to lead when leading is helpful and to make room when it is not. There is heat in how they feel about you, but the heat is paired with a steady, grown-up confidence that is rare and worth honouring.\n\nWhat they may not say outright is how much they respect you. The King of Wands does not extend admiration easily, and when he does, it is meant. You are not a passing interest. You are someone he has looked at with full attention and chosen on purpose, and the choosing itself is the love language. His feelings are warm, focused and durable. He is in this because he wants to be, and he intends to keep being in it until the situation tells him otherwise.`,
    feelingsFaqs: [
      { q: 'What does King of Wands mean as feelings?', a: 'The King of Wands as feelings describes mature, decisive, openly directed attraction. The other person has chosen you on purpose, with full attention, and they intend to act on that choice consistently. Their feelings are warm but unembroidered — they do not perform; they decide and they show up. Expect deliberate plans, generous leadership, clear interest expressed with the confidence of someone who has lived enough to know what is worth pursuing. This is grown-up love, and it tends to last as long as both people remain in it on purpose.' },
      { q: 'Does King of Wands mean they are serious about me?', a: 'Yes, decisively so. The King of Wands does not invest his attention casually. When he chooses someone, he has usually thought about it carefully and decided that the connection is worth his time. He is not the type to keep his options open or hedge his interest. If he is showing up for you with the steady, confident energy of this card, you can take that seriously. He means what he is doing, and he intends to keep meaning it. Receive the directness as the genuine commitment it is.' },
      { q: 'What does King of Wands reversed mean as feelings?', a: 'Reversed, the King of Wands describes maturity that has tipped into control, arrogance, or emotional unavailability. The feeling may be real, but the expression has narrowed — decisions made without consulting you, warmth that has gone underground behind provision and pride, or a man who has retreated into his role to avoid feeling what is harder. Read context carefully. Some Kings reversed need a direct conversation about partnership. Others need patience and the refusal to compete with their armour. Both call for someone who can stay grounded while the King finds his way back to softness.' },
      { q: 'Is King of Wands a sign of marriage?', a: 'It can be. The King of Wands as feelings describes a person who is capable of long-term commitment and who tends to make their choices with the seriousness that real partnership requires. He is not always the most romantic in the obvious sense, but he is among the most reliable. If marriage or a comparable long-term commitment is what you are hoping for, this card is encouraging — provided his decisiveness is matched by your own readiness to be chosen with that level of intention. He wants a partner, not an audience.' },
    ],
  },
}
